The paper deals with a centrality measure based on network analysis, which is a common topic in several sub-categories of computer science. The focus on network connectivity and node ranking suggests that cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is the most likely sub-category. The use of adjacency matrices and exponential functions points towards cs.SD (Systems and Control) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as possible sub-categories. The numerical studies and comparisons with other centrality measures suggest cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the use of real-world networks and the emphasis on computational efficiency suggest cs.LG (Machine Learning) as a less likely but still possible sub-category.
